        <body>       
                
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                February 28<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1887<lb/></p>
            <p>Reverend Sir&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I take pleasure in<lb/> submitting to you as President of<lb/> the Faculty of the Jew. Theol. Sem&#45;<lb/>inary the first report of the stand&#45;<lb/>ing of the preparatory class under<lb/> my charge.  Since the 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi> inst. I<lb/> have instructed the class<del>es</del> regularly<lb/> on the following days&#59; Sundays from<lb/> 3 to 5 P.M&#44; Mondays&#44; Tuesdays and<lb/> Thursdays from 4 to 6 P. M.  We have<lb/> taken &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; the 4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> chapter of<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; and I have delivered one lecture on<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the history of the Hebrew language<lb/> and one on introduction to the Tal&#45;<lb/>mud.  In conjunction with Rev. Dr. F.<lb/> De Sola Mendes of the curriculum<lb/> committee the course of studies for<lb/> the current scholastic year has been fixed as follows&#59;<lb/> Sundays entire session &#91;Hebrew&#93; with &#91;Hebrew&#93; and<lb/> explanations&#44; Mondays one hour &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> and one hour grammar&#44; Tuesdays<lb/> one hour &#91;Hebrew&#93; and one hour history.  Thurs&#45;<lb/>days entire session &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I am en&#45;<lb/>tirely satisfied&#44; indeed thoroughly<lb/> pleased with the character and abilities<lb/> of the boys.  I find them bright&#44;<lb/> intelligent and well behaved and am<lb/> convinced that if the blessing of<lb/> God but rest on our work&#44; we shall<lb/> be able to rear out of these boys<lb/> Rabbis whose learning&#44; piety and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>personal worth cannot fail to redound to<lb/> the benefit of conservative Judaism.<lb/>  Two of the students&#44; Simson and Kurtz&#44; es&#45;<lb/>pecially the latter&#44; are hampered in<lb/> their progress by deficient acquaintance<lb/> with English&#44; but this obstacle will&#44; with<lb/> time and the efforts they are making&#44;<lb/> undoubtedly grow continually less.<lb/>  I have the honor to remain&#44; Reverend and<lb/> Dear Sir&#44;<lb/> very sincerely yours<lb/> Bernard Drachman Ph. D.<lb/> Preceptor<lb/></p>
            </body>
